1
00:00:53,690 --> 00:00:55,024
Some mornings,

2
00:00:55,280 --> 00:00:57,379
I wake up crying without knowing why.

3
00:00:58,460 --> 00:01:00,846
That sort of thing happens now and again.

4
00:01:01,680 --> 00:01:03,789
Whatever the dream was I had,

5
00:01:04,103 --> 00:01:05,697
I can never remember it.

6
00:01:06,172 --> 00:01:06,992
But...

7
00:01:07,805 --> 00:01:08,665
But...

8
00:01:09,327 --> 00:01:11,999
The only thing that does last when I wake up

9
00:01:12,117 --> 00:01:13,693
This is a sense of loss

10
00:01:14,460 --> 00:01:17,009
which lingers for a long time afterwards.

11
00:01:23,558 --> 00:01:26,049
I'm always searching for something,

12
00:01:26,280 --> 00:01:27,725
or someone.

13
00:01:28,424 --> 00:01:31,207
I've been consumed by this feeling

14
00:01:31,701 --> 00:01:33,241
ever since that day.

15
00:01:34,658 --> 00:01:38,044
The day a star fell.

16
00:01:38,777 --> 00:01:40,071
It was almost like...

17
00:01:40,320 --> 00:01:42,477
...like seeing something out of a dream.

18
00:01:43,692 --> 00:01:45,279
Nothing more or less...

19
00:01:46,349 --> 00:01:48,922
...than a breathtaking view.

20
00:03:44,070 --> 00:03:44,868
Taki.

21
00:03:45,897 --> 00:03:46,729
Taki.

22
00:03:47,967 --> 00:03:48,840
Taki.

23
00:03:50,566 --> 00:03:52,000
Don't you remember?

24
00:03:55,286 --> 00:03:56,420
My name is...

25
00:03:58,275 --> 00:03:59,255
...Mitsuha!

26
00:04:35,281 --> 00:04:37,784
Sis, what are you doing?

27
00:04:37,907 --> 00:04:41,166
Whoa. They're so realistic feeling.

28
00:04:41,950 --> 00:04:43,755
"Sis"? Me?

29
00:04:44,065 --> 00:04:45,703
Are you still asleep?

30
00:04:45,827 --> 00:04:46,802
Breakfast time!

31
00:04:46,900 --> 00:04:47,860
Hurry up!

32
00:05:09,950 --> 00:05:13,253
Wha...? What?!

33
00:05:19,879 --> 00:05:22,305
Do you wanna have any a last night's fish, Grandma?

34
00:05:22,400 --> 00:05:23,419
You can eat it.

35
00:05:24,665 --> 00:05:25,349
Morning.

36
00:05:25,374 --> 00:05:26,138
Morning.

37
00:05:26,184 --> 00:05:27,864
Lazy butt! You're so slow!

38
00:05:27,971 --> 00:05:29,631
I'll fix breakfast tomorrow.

39
00:05:35,770 --> 00:05:36,983
Oh, that's a lot.

40
00:05:37,157 --> 00:05:38,149
Oh, well!

41
00:05:38,805 --> 00:05:40,612
You're back to normal today.

42
00:05:40,717 --> 00:05:43,137
You were so crazy yesterday.

43
00:05:43,162 --> 00:05:44,970
What do you mean "crazy"?

44
00:05:46,683 --> 00:05:48,543
Attention citizens of Itomori.

45
00:05:49,226 --> 00:05:50,315
Good morning.

46
00:05:50,603 --> 00:05:53,869
This is an official announcement from Itomori Town Hall.

47
00:05:54,320 --> 00:05:56,767
It is in regards to the mayoral election.

48
00:05:57,195 --> 00:05:59,875
The election will be held on the 20th of next month.

49
00:06:00,696 --> 00:06:03,673
The election committee would
like to remind everyone that...

50
00:06:06,750 --> 00:06:09,916
A comet that comes only once every 1,200 years

51
00:06:09,997 --> 00:06:12,353
will finally be headed our way in a month.

52
00:06:12,650 --> 00:06:17,006
The comet will be visible to the naked eye for
several days once it approaches the Earth...

53
00:06:17,050 --> 00:06:19,105
Just make up with him already, okay?

54
00:06:19,238 --> 00:06:20,393
It's an adult matter.

55
00:06:20,431 --> 00:06:24,825
According to JAXA's spokesperson, they're
preparing for The celestia show of the millennium.

56
00:06:41,389 --> 00:06:42,620
We're leaving!

57
00:06:46,380 --> 00:06:47,905
I can't wait till the festival!

58
00:06:47,940 --> 00:06:49,434
It's gonna be so much fun!

59
00:07:03,464 --> 00:07:05,244
Study hard, Sis!

60
00:07:08,269 --> 00:07:08,910
Ow!

61
00:07:10,650 --> 00:07:11,958
Mitsuha!

62
00:07:12,144 --> 00:07:14,243
Good morning, Saya. Morning, Teshi.

63
00:07:14,310 --> 00:07:15,023
Morning.

64
00:07:15,120 --> 00:07:16,834
Come on! Would you get off already?

65
00:07:16,990 --> 00:07:18,109
What for, meanie?

66
00:07:18,141 --> 00:07:19,056
'Cause you're heavy.

67
00:07:19,080 --> 00:07:19,931
Hey, that's rude.`

68
00:07:19,950 --> 00:07:22,187
You know, I've gotta say, you two make a great couple.

69
00:07:22,210 --> 00:07:22,186
No we don't!

70
00:07:22,210 --> 00:07:23,368
No we don't!

71
00:07:25,896 --> 00:07:28,489
Oh, I see you actually bothered to do your hair today.

72
00:07:28,557 --> 00:07:29,705
Wait, what?

73
00:07:29,750 --> 00:07:32,770
Oh, yeah, what happened?
Did your grandma exorcise all your demons?

74
00:07:32,800 --> 00:07:33,552
Exorcise?

75
00:07:33,579 --> 00:07:35,668
Something totally possessed your body.

76
00:07:36,137 --> 00:07:38,691
Would just give it a rest with all this occult nonsense?

77
00:07:39,061 --> 00:07:41,346
Mitsuha's gotta be feeling stressed enough as it is,

78
00:07:41,370 --> 00:07:41,712
Right?

79
00:07:41,740 --> 00:07:43,368
What're you guys talking about?

80
00:07:43,596 --> 00:07:44,863
Are you feeling okay?

81
00:07:46,798 --> 00:07:47,978
And above all,

82
00:07:48,345 --> 00:07:53,496
restoring the town's fiscal health so we
can continue our revitalization project!

83
00:07:53,706 --> 00:07:56,074
It's only when all these things are achieved

84
00:07:56,120 --> 00:07:59,424
that we can create a safe and secure community!

85
00:07:59,839 --> 00:08:02,206
As the incumbent, my administration has...

86
00:08:02,240 --> 00:08:05,012
Miyamizu's gonna get another term anyway.

87
00:08:05,040 --> 00:08:07,604
I hear he's been doling out the pork, just between us.

88
00:08:08,188 --> 00:08:09,634
Hey, Miyamizu.

89
00:08:09,650 --> 00:08:10,868
Morning.

90
00:08:11,460 --> 00:08:14,718
Looks like the mayor and the
contractors' kid are pretty cozy too.

91
00:08:14,750 --> 00:08:16,126
Ew.

92
00:08:16,140 --> 00:08:18,905
...and improve the quality of
life of each and every resident.

93
00:08:20,764 --> 00:08:22,125
Mitsuha!

94
00:08:22,670 --> 00:08:24,304
Stand up straight when you're walking!

95
00:08:25,650 --> 00:08:27,343
Oh, he's tough on his family.

96
00:08:27,360 --> 00:08:28,717
Well, that's the mayor for ya.

97
00:08:28,930 --> 00:08:29,861
Awkward.

98
00:08:29,916 --> 00:08:31,183
Sucks to be her.

99
00:08:32,244 --> 00:08:33,345
Mitsuha.

100
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:36,283
In front of everyone...

101
00:08:50,320 --> 00:08:53,579
"Two-light" That's the origin of the word "twilight."

102
00:08:53,873 --> 00:08:56,070
I'm sure everyone here knows that word.

103
00:08:56,700 --> 00:08:59,875
It's dusk. A time when it's neither day nor night.

104
00:09:00,460 --> 00:09:02,331
When the border between worlds blur,

105
00:09:02,583 --> 00:09:05,233
and one might encounter something not human.

106
00:09:06,417 --> 00:09:09,839
Another older term for it is "dusk-light."

107
00:09:10,179 --> 00:09:13,187
Some people also call it "golden hour."

108
00:09:13,340 --> 00:09:14,493
What about magic hour?

109
00:09:14,530 --> 00:09:16,207
It's something my grandma says.

110
00:09:16,300 --> 00:09:19,755
Well, golden hour and magic
hour are technically the same.

111
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:22,523
But it's a term that mostly photographers use.

112
00:09:23,100 --> 00:09:25,694
Well, she does take a lot of pictures.

113
00:09:28,020 --> 00:09:30,584
Okay, next, Miyamizu!

114
00:09:30,700 --> 00:09:32,225
Uh! Yes!

115
00:09:32,336 --> 00:09:35,544
Well, I can see that  you remember your own name today.

116
00:09:38,768 --> 00:09:40,798
You don't remember?

117
00:09:41,606 --> 00:09:45,440
Well, believe it or not, you forgot where
your own desk and locker were yesterday.

118
00:09:45,728 --> 00:09:49,460
Plus you had the worst case of bed head,
and you didn't have your ribbon on either.

119
00:09:52,230 --> 00:09:54,309
What? No way!

120
00:09:54,430 --> 00:09:56,798
Yeah, it was like you had amnesia or something.

121
00:09:57,085 --> 00:10:01,697
Now that you mention it, I do feel like
I've been having weird dreams lately.

122
00:10:01,820 --> 00:10:04,524
Like a dream about someone else's life?

123
00:10:04,955 --> 00:10:07,408
Ugh... It's all so fuzzy.

124
00:10:08,116 --> 00:10:10,341
Wait a sec. I've got it!

125
00:10:10,680 --> 00:10:12,462
It's memories from a previous life!

126
00:10:12,480 --> 00:10:16,252
Or maybe your subconscious linked to the
Everett interpretation of the multiverse!

127
00:10:16,290 --> 00:10:17,488
Keep your fool mouth shut!

128
00:10:17,500 --> 00:10:20,955
Wait a minute, Teshi! Don't tell me
you're the one who wrote in my notebook!

129
00:10:22,730 --> 00:10:23,876
Forget it.

130
00:10:25,008 --> 00:10:28,692
But you really were acting just a
little funny yesterday, Mitsuha.

131
00:10:29,459 --> 00:10:31,121
You been feeling okay?

132
00:10:32,303 --> 00:10:33,426
That's what's weird.

133
00:10:34,164 --> 00:10:35,331
I feel fine.

134
00:10:35,471 --> 00:10:36,973
Maybe it's from stress.

135
00:10:37,090 --> 00:10:39,545
Y'know, you've got that ritual coming soon, don'tcha?

136
00:10:39,570 --> 00:10:41,550
Aww! Don't remind me!

137
00:10:41,740 --> 00:10:43,878
I can't stand this place anymore.

138
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:46,178
It's too small and towny.

139
00:10:46,336 --> 00:10:49,827
I wanna graduate already and
go to Tokyo as soon as I can!

140
00:10:50,844 --> 00:10:52,264
Can't say I blame you.

141
00:10:52,571 --> 00:10:55,233
There really is nothing at all in this town.

142
00:10:56,960 --> 00:10:59,653
There's only one train that stops here every two hours.

143
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:01,452
And all the store closes at nine o'clock.

144
00:11:01,563 --> 00:11:03,450
No bookstores, no dentists.

145
00:11:03,470 --> 00:11:06,084
But two cocktail lounges for whatever reason.

146
00:11:06,110 --> 00:11:07,189
No jobs in town.

147
00:11:07,200 --> 00:11:08,220
No one datable.

148
00:11:08,230 --> 00:11:10,210
Even the days are too short!

149
00:11:12,330 --> 00:11:13,348
You know what?!

150
00:11:13,550 --> 00:11:14,577
No, what?

151
00:11:15,892 --> 00:11:18,325
Forget that stuff. Why don't we go to a café?

152
00:11:18,350 --> 00:11:18,686
A café?

153
00:11:18,710 --> 00:11:19,560
Really?

154
00:11:20,010 --> 00:11:21,209
Where!?

155
00:11:25,797 --> 00:11:26,749
Hello, kids.

156
00:11:26,778 --> 00:11:27,704
Hi there!

157
00:11:33,030 --> 00:11:34,683
How is this a café?

158
00:11:34,700 --> 00:11:36,730
Like this town's got a café'.

159
00:11:36,980 --> 00:11:39,007
Mitsuha just went straight home.

160
00:11:40,528 --> 00:11:42,988
Things have gotta be really rough for her right now.

161
00:11:43,174 --> 00:11:45,414
She's on center stage and all.

162
00:11:45,440 --> 00:11:46,296
Yeah.

163
00:11:49,630 --> 00:11:51,224
Hey, Teshi.

164
00:11:52,816 --> 00:11:55,476
What're you gonna do after you graduate high school?

165
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:57,076
Where'd that come from?

166
00:11:57,150 --> 00:11:58,702
You talking about the future?

167
00:12:00,440 --> 00:12:01,486
I don't know.

168
00:12:01,830 --> 00:12:05,396
I think I'll probably just end up living in this
town, you know? Same as ever.

169
00:12:21,829 --> 00:12:23,709
I wanna do what you're doing.

170
00:12:23,823 --> 00:12:26,504
It's still too soon for you to try, Yotsuha.

171
00:12:26,537 --> 00:12:28,891
Listen to the thread's voice.

172
00:12:29,210 --> 00:12:32,263
When you twine it round and round like this,

173
00:12:32,263 --> 00:12:35,583
feelings will start flowing between you and the thread.

174
00:12:35,800 --> 00:12:38,295
It's not like threads talk.

175
00:12:38,320 --> 00:12:40,167
She's telling you to focus.

176
00:12:40,874 --> 00:12:46,228
Etched within our braided cords is a
thousand years' worth of Itomori's history.

177
00:12:46,500 --> 00:12:50,238
Listen, something happened 200 years ago.

178
00:12:50,533 --> 00:12:51,926
Here she goes.

179
00:12:52,146 --> 00:12:56,225
The bathroom of sandal maker
Mayugoro Yamazaki caught on fire,

180
00:12:56,319 --> 00:12:58,751
and this whole area burned down.

181
00:12:59,206 --> 00:13:01,906
The shrine and old documents were destroyed.

182
00:13:02,829 --> 00:13:04,143
This is known as...

183
00:13:04,249 --> 00:13:05,884
Mayugoro's Great Fire.

184
00:13:06,078 --> 00:13:08,095
They named the fire after him?

185
00:13:08,188 --> 00:13:09,990
I feel bad for Mayugoro.

186
00:13:11,314 --> 00:13:14,888
The meaning behind our festivals
was lost because of that.

187
00:13:15,120 --> 00:13:17,108
Only the surface was left.

188
00:13:17,760 --> 00:13:21,601
But even if those words are gone,
the tradition shouldn't fade.

189
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:26,041
That's the Miyamizu Shrine's duty, our important task.

190
00:13:28,735 --> 00:13:32,619
Despite all that, that son-in-law of mine...

191
00:13:32,798 --> 00:13:38,244
Abandoning the Shinto priesthood and leaving
this house were bad enough, but politics?

192
00:13:38,330 --> 00:13:40,167
Oh! He's hopeless.

193
00:13:41,378 --> 00:13:42,978
Have another, Mr. Foreman.

194
00:13:43,071 --> 00:13:45,288
The site we've got is a tricky one, that's for sure.

195
00:13:45,310 --> 00:13:46,607
Whoa!

196
00:13:46,620 --> 00:13:49,174
I'll be counting on your help again for this election.

197
00:13:49,200 --> 00:13:50,289
Leave it to me.

198
00:13:50,300 --> 00:13:54,201
You'll get the votes from the Kadoiri
and Sakagami districts, guaranteed.

199
00:13:54,240 --> 00:13:55,596
How's the dating scene?

200
00:13:55,610 --> 00:13:56,976
It ain’t easy, that's for sure!

201
00:13:59,240 --> 00:14:01,185
Smells like corruption in there.

202
00:14:01,460 --> 00:14:03,138
What're you talking about?

203
00:14:03,586 --> 00:14:05,838
We're gonna need two or three more bottles.

204
00:14:05,860 --> 00:14:07,256
Yes, dear.

205
00:14:07,270 --> 00:14:09,903
Katsuhiko, you're gonna help
out at the site this weekend.

206
00:14:09,930 --> 00:14:12,920
We'll be using explosives, so you better study up.

207
00:14:13,508 --> 00:14:14,409
What was that?

208
00:14:14,496 --> 00:14:15,311
Got it!

209
00:14:29,125 --> 00:14:31,678
Guess we both can't stand things here.

210
00:14:50,050 --> 00:14:51,644
Is that Yotsuha?

211
00:14:51,660 --> 00:14:53,036
She's all grown up.

212
00:14:53,050 --> 00:14:55,852
They're lookers all right, just like their mother.

213
00:14:57,470 --> 00:14:58,204
Hey-a.

214
00:14:58,799 --> 00:14:59,559
Hey.

215
00:15:32,198 --> 00:15:34,417
World's oldest kind of saké.

216
00:15:34,702 --> 00:15:40,520
By chewing on rice, spitting it out, and then
letting it ferment naturally, it becomes alcohol.

217
00:15:40,600 --> 00:15:42,560
<i>Kuchikamizake.</i>

218
00:15:42,716 --> 00:15:44,966
Do the gods really appreciate that?

219
00:15:44,990 --> 00:15:45,841
The way it's...

220
00:15:45,850 --> 00:15:47,266
Yeah! Of course they do!

221
00:15:49,510 --> 00:15:51,619
Hey, check it out. It's Miyamizu.

222
00:15:57,606 --> 00:15:59,486
Uh! I'd never do that!

223
00:15:59,850 --> 00:16:01,622
And in front of everybody.

224
00:16:01,714 --> 00:16:03,184
Embarrassing, right?

225
00:16:17,540 --> 00:16:19,247
You should try to cheer up, Sis.

226
00:16:19,942 --> 00:16:22,870
Who cares if a few of the kids
from your school saw all that?

227
00:16:22,900 --> 00:16:25,672
It must be nice for you, not being a teenager.

228
00:16:26,282 --> 00:16:27,427
Hey, I know,

229
00:16:27,557 --> 00:16:29,519
you should just sell <i>kuchikamizake</i>

230
00:16:29,632 --> 00:16:30,877
and move to Tokyo.

231
00:16:30,890 --> 00:16:35,664
I bet you could sell it with all sorts of
stuff, like photos and making-of videos.

232
00:16:35,760 --> 00:16:39,347
Oh! And then you could call it "Shrine Maiden Saké."

233
00:16:39,574 --> 00:16:40,983
You'll make butt-loads!

234
00:16:44,539 --> 00:16:46,507
I can't! There are liquor laws!

235
00:16:48,200 --> 00:16:49,987
That's what you have a problem with?

236
00:16:56,260 --> 00:16:58,242
I hate this town!

237
00:16:58,830 --> 00:17:01,187
I hate this life too!

238
00:17:01,367 --> 00:17:04,976
Please make me a handsome Tokyo boy in my next life!

239
00:17:10,074 --> 00:17:11,721
What a jackass.

240
00:17:43,397 --> 00:17:44,273
Ouch...

241
00:17:54,080 --> 00:17:55,090
Where?

242
00:18:06,370 --> 00:18:08,332
Somethings... there.

243
00:18:22,669 --> 00:18:23,383
Ow!

244
00:18:23,540 --> 00:18:25,083
Taki! You up?

245
00:18:27,873 --> 00:18:30,018
It was your turn to cook breakfast, wasn't it?

246
00:18:30,148 --> 00:18:31,169
Did you sleep in?

247
00:18:31,316 --> 00:18:32,526
Uh. I'm sorry.

248
00:18:33,890 --> 00:18:35,475
Uh, I'm heading out.

249
00:18:35,945 --> 00:18:37,045
Finish the miso.

250
00:18:37,856 --> 00:18:38,648
O-Okay.

251
00:18:39,026 --> 00:18:41,455
Make sure that you go to school even if you're late.

252
00:18:41,793 --> 00:18:42,377
See ya.

253
00:18:43,460 --> 00:18:44,668
Have a nice day!

254
00:18:56,011 --> 00:18:57,424
What a weird dream.

255
00:19:03,075 --> 00:19:07,495
Huh? It's from... Tsukasa? Who's that?

256
00:19:17,260 --> 00:19:18,638
I gotta go pee.

257
00:19:28,191 --> 00:19:29,104
Way too real.

258
00:20:40,809 --> 00:20:42,376
I'm in Tokyo!

259
00:20:49,955 --> 00:20:51,162
Where did you get this?

260
00:20:51,228 --> 00:20:51,622
Daikanyama.

261
00:20:51,680 --> 00:20:53,670
Guess who's opening our next gig?

262
00:20:53,739 --> 00:20:56,579
Hey, it's skip club stuff today and catch a movie.

263
00:21:01,650 --> 00:21:02,679
Taki.

264
00:21:04,396 --> 00:21:05,869
Can't believe you got in at noon.

265
00:21:06,240 --> 00:21:07,309
Come on, let's grab lunch!

266
00:21:08,701 --> 00:21:10,381
You ignored my text too.

267
00:21:11,254 --> 00:21:12,367
Uh, Mister Tsukasa?

